When the user saves the image and then exits the app in the normal way (i.e., without any additional edits), Paintroid can delete this temporary image data.

Background: 
* This is a two-star feedback of a user on Google Play: "Айтуар Мұхарам Mar 15, 2020 at 12:50 PM Auto-translated from Russian - The application is good. BUT WHEN I DRAWED THE WHOLE 2 HOURS AT THE LAST MOMENT, THE APPLICATION JUST TURNED OFF AND THE FIGURE HAS NOT BEEN SAVED. And I tried so hard. It was a shame. He just laid. And I deleted it ." 
* There were other similar reviews also, e.g., "Spyro The Dragon Mar 8, 2020 at 12:50 AM Auto-translated from Spanish - It is a very good app in general, even without pocket code, but, constantly crashing me for no reason, it is very annoying since sometimes I lose progress in what I was doing or even lose what I was doing completely". 
* And here's another one: "Jacob Howie Jan 25, 2020 at 6:19 PM ... if you go off the app (not close it, just visit Google for instance) it will delete your current project." 

This is also a simple solution for similar such cases, e.g., for Huawei phones with an aggressive battery saving mode as its default.

If we keep two such temporary copies, and only delete the previous one once the current one has been safely saved on persistent memory, there's no danger that data is lost while overwriting of the saved copy. If the saved copy is corrupted after restart, just use the earlier one. Only a single image data needs to be remembered in this way most of the time (besides when a new one is stored, for a short time, i.e., until the new one is safely stored). Once the app is restarted without being called with an image already selected, Paintroid could first check whether such temporary image data is present and is recent (within the last 60 minutes, e.g., maybe after a phone call), and if so, restore it, so that the user can continue from that place. It is also possible to ask the user in a small dialog whether he/she wants to resume, e.g., if the time is more than a minute ago. For below one minute, it should resume without asking --- there's always the option to delete the canvas anyway. It is OK if only the very last actions are lost, which might be unavoidable, but at least most of the work will have been saved and remembered. to set the center point, i.e., no special additional information is needed, it is just the image that gets enlarged (or smaller on some borders --- let\'s try to make it not unecessarily larger than needed). For an algorithm how to do it, see our Scratch to Catrobat converter code. Paintroid\'s auto-crop tool/function is already doing something a bit similar. This needs some kind of UI. Added button "Set center" in the Transform tool, since it resembles the auto-crop but changes the size and placement of the canvas in a different way. Interactively, it allows to move the center, shows the x=0, y=0 axes as thin lines (up to canvas border) at the new center point, and allows to move this center cross in different directions by panning anywhere on the canvas. The enclosing canvas borders should change in accordance. Confirm via a checkmark at the top right, or by leaving the "Set center" mode or the tool (like we discussed for the text tool). "Jitter" movements due to lifting the finger should be ignored. 

See https://jira.catrob.at/projects/CATROID/issues/CATROID-311 and PR at https://github.com/Catrobat/Catroid/pull/3393 for how this was successfully done in Catroid.  

See https://youtu.be/zl2Pn-f_HQQ for a video showing the current behavior with the stamp tool, when the zoom factor is high. The faulty "jumping" is repeated three times towards the end of the video.

"Jitter" movements due to lifting the finger should be ignored. See ', 'to': None, 'toString': 'As a user I want tools to stay at their last intuitive position when lifting the finger. "Jitter" movements due to lifting the finger should be ignored. 

See https://jira.catrob.at/projects/CATROID/issues/CATROID-311 and PR at https://github.com/Catrobat/Catroid/pull/3393 for how this was successfully done in Catroid.  

See https://youtu.be/zl2Pn-f_HQQ for a video showing the current behavior with the stamp tool, when the zoom factor is high. The faulty "jumping" is repeated three times towards the end of the video.

The same also happens with the shape, text, transform, and import-image tools, i.e., all tools that have a quadratic selection.

All these cases can easily be corrected in the same way as in Catroid, see links above.'}]}]}

'2019-02-13T12:00:06.240+0100', 'items': [{'field': 'description', 'fieldtype': 'jira', 'from': None, 'fromString': 'There is a bug in the behaviour of "New Image".
 New image should only clear the current image, without discarding the previous URI.
 * Rename "New Image" to "Discard Image"
 * Don't discard the previously chosen URI

For reference, excerpt of my conversation with Wolfgang:
{noformat}
Wolfgang Slany [14:57]
Better name instead of New image?

Thomas Schwengler [14:57]
Clear image? Reset image? I'm not sure
Well, since you can also use it to get a new image from the camera it would still be misleading :sweat_smile:
Should this be the same in standalone mode? I.e. should new image always keep the currently saved position?


Wolfgang Slany [15:04]
Please discuss this with @vesna. Maybe  "Discard image" would fit. For the standalone version, if the button is renamed to "Discard image" it should overwrite the original image.
{noformat}', 'to': None, 'toString': 'The behavior of "New Image" should be changed for the integrated version.
 New image should only clear the current image, without discarding the previous URI.
 * Rename "New Image" to "Clear Canvas"
 * Don't discard the previously chosen URI

For reference, excerpt of my conversation with Wolfgang:
{noformat}
Wolfgang Slany [14:57]
Better name instead of New image?

Thomas Schwengler [14:57]
Clear image? Reset image? I'm not sure
Well, since you can also use it to get a new image from the camera it would still be misleading :sweat_smile:
Should this be the same in standalone mode? I.e. should new image always keep the currently saved position?


Wolfgang Slany [15:04]
Please discuss this with @vesna. Maybe  "Discard image" would fit. For the standalone version, if the button is renamed to "Discard image" it should overwrite the original image.
